<h1>🧼 RS001 Week 6 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Clean Every Input Safely · <strong>Course:</strong> Text Adventure (Python) · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week you think about how <code>.strip().lower()</code> cleans <strong>every</strong> <code>ask()</code> in your game, and how a game can accept several spellings of the same answer — Korean, English, short forms — so almost any sensible input works. You will read code closely and explain it in your own words.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧠 Words to know: <strong>clean</strong>, <strong>strip</strong>, <strong>lower</strong>, <strong>in</strong>, <strong>spelling</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Run it in your head and write what you think happens.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">d = &quot;  RIGHT &quot;
d = d.strip().lower()
game.say(f&quot;[{d}]&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What is printed inside the brackets?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">d = game.ask(&quot;way?&quot;)
d = d.strip().lower()
if d in [&quot;left&quot;, &quot;l&quot;, &quot;왼쪽&quot;]:
    d = &quot;left&quot;
game.say(d)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The player types <code>L</code>. What single word is printed?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">d = &quot;Left&quot;
d = d.lower().strip()
game.say(f&quot;[{d}]&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Here <code>.lower()</code> runs before <code>.strip()</code>. Does the result change? Why or why not?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, fix it on paper, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This should accept <code>"left"</code>, <code>"l"</code>, or <code>"왼쪽"</code> and turn them all into <code>"left"</code>. Right now it only matches the full word <code>"left"</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">d = game.ask(&quot;way?&quot;).strip().lower()
if d == &quot;left&quot;:
    d = &quot;left&quot;
game.say(d)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> swap <code>==</code> for <code>in [ ... ]</code> and list the spellings you want to allow.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — Two inputs (a direction and an action) should both be cleaned. Right now only the first one is, so the action still has spaces and capitals.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">direction = game.ask(&quot;way?&quot;).strip().lower()
action = game.ask(&quot;do what?&quot;)
game.say(f&quot;{direction} / {action}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the second input needs the same cleaning treatment.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The match list should be in <strong>lowercase</strong> so the cleaned input can find it. Right now the list has a capital letter, so a cleaned <code>"left"</code> never matches.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">d = game.ask(&quot;way?&quot;).strip().lower()
if d in [&quot;Left&quot;, &quot;l&quot;]:
    d = &quot;left&quot;
game.say(d)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> after <code>.lower()</code>, the input is lowercase — the list must be too.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Read this working example slowly. It cleans the player's answer and accepts several spellings of "left".</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">direction = game.ask(&quot;Which way? (left/right)&quot;)
direction = direction.strip().lower()
if direction in [&quot;left&quot;, &quot;l&quot;, &quot;왼쪽&quot;]:
    direction = &quot;left&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What does <code>.strip()</code> remove from the player's answer?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What does <code>.lower()</code> do to a capital letter the player typed?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why must the words in the list <code>["left", "l", "왼쪽"]</code> all be lowercase?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>The player types <code>"  Left "</code>. After line 2, what is the value of <code>direction</code>? Does the <code>if</code> match?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is it helpful to turn <code>"l"</code> and <code>"왼쪽"</code> both into <code>"left"</code> before the rest of the game runs?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

